Is it possible to regulate systemic risks?
MILAN – Over the past two years, the global economy has been hit hard by financial instability and sudden changes in market dynamics.
Other events of this kind are likely, because following the crisis, the global economy is imbalanced in many aspects, particularly from the perspective of sovereign debts and the structure of global demand.
Systemic risks are the source of most crises and present a challenge for several reasons.
Firstly, they are not easy to detect with certainty and even more difficult to prove.
Next, predicting the exact moment of the breaking point (when bubbles burst, when markets are paralyzed, and when credit is no longer available) is, and will undoubtedly remain, beyond our analytical capabilities.
Finally, crises are strongly nonlinear events that occur without prior warning signs.
The periodic manifestations of instability impose a high social cost on those least responsible for them.
If this pattern were to repeat, it could undermine confidence in financial markets and regulatory authorities, a loss of confidence that could herald excessive regulations, state intervention, and disengagement from globalization.
But the problem is even more serious.
The financial and economic crisis is turning into a sovereign debt crisis in advanced countries.
Economic and financial imbalances can lead to a dangerous fiscal imbalance, characterized by a deterioration of tax revenues and an increase in bail-out expenditures.
The International Monetary Fund estimates that up to 75 percent of the "fiscal packages" of advanced economies include non-discretionary counter-cyclical measures.
Undetected imbalances and systemic risks make fiscal policies that appear prudent in fact not prudent.
Spain, for example, had no fiscal deficit at the beginning of the crisis.
But his revenues and expenditures were largely determined by a real estate bubble linked to very high debt.
An extreme fiscal imbalance can also lead to a "growth trap" in which fiscal consolidation has such a negative effect on growth that it cancels itself out.
Greece is undoubtedly a typical example of this.
In the end, the only way out is to reset the value of liabilities through restructuring or through inflation.
If systemic risks can cause this kind of sequential cascade imbalance, sovereign states must be attentive to the danger, capable of identifying the emergence of a systemic risk and quickly taking corrective measures.
Detailed new legislative frameworks, focusing on capital requirements and leverage, transparency, ratings and other sources of information, incentives, conflicts of interest and limits on the size of financial institutions, consumer protection and resolution mechanisms are soon to be adopted.
The hope is that these reforms will reduce the probability and severity of systemic risks.
But this will not in any way resolve the problem of global imbalances and other factors contributing to and signaling instability.
In addition to and complementing new legislative frameworks, a comprehensive system for monitoring systemic risks is necessary.
However, some politicians and leading analysts believe that such a system, aimed at identifying and containing systemic risks, is futile.
The incomplete models of risk dynamics and a complex, ever-changing global financial system make risk detection, according to them, either impossible or so prone to error that such an effort would be unproductive.
Asset bubbles are almost impossible to identify without error.
If skeptics are right, we must then accept that we will periodically be in a situation of financial and fiscal instability without being able to predict it in advance.
We should then also accept a much more cautious fiscal policy than the one we considered necessary just three years ago.
In the field of statistics and decision-making under conditions of uncertainty, errors are inevitable.
There are two types of errors: one consists of rejecting a true proposition and the other is accepting a false proposition.
Let us call them RQV (rejected when true) and AQF (accepted when false).
The question can be phrased as follows: in the context of detecting and responding to systemic risks, which of these two types of errors has the highest probable cost?
Opponents of prudent supervision of systemic risks have two different positions.
One of them is that the AQF error will not occur, because there are no reliable indicators of a potentially increasing instability.
Looking for such a sign is a waste of time.
Instability occurs instantaneously.
But this position seems fallacious.
For example, during the 2008 crisis, some analysts issued warnings and some investors took note of them.
However, it must be admitted that these warnings were perhaps not sufficient to be irrefutable and they certainly did not foresee the breaking point.
They were nevertheless undeniably signs.
The second position is that there are indeed precursor signs, but that they are so unreliable that taking measures would do more harm than good.
This viewpoint implies that AQF has a likely higher cost than RQV, because there are many false positive elements and/or that the remedy is worse than the disease.
There is no doubt that there are costs associated with AQF error.
But RQV is also costly, as we have seen, so that the aggregated negative effect of reacting to false positives (AQF) must be significant to be convincing.
I am not convinced, for my part.
There may be a deeper trend at play.
Whether in business or investments, choices are constantly made under conditions of uncertainty and errors are frequent.
The default position of decision-makers in advanced countries seems, on the contrary, to be that proactive and preemptive measures require a high level of certainty, linked to the deeply rooted belief that financial markets are stable and self-regulating.
If one believes that market instability is rare, it is then reasonable to refuse to act unless there are good reasons to do so.
But in light of past experiences, the idea that the global financial system is only exceptionally unstable or on a downward slope is at least questionable.
Based on new theories and experiences, we could eventually conclude that political responses to systemic risks are impossible to develop and that the cost of AQF errors is higher than the cost of RQV errors.
But we should at least attempt the experiment, and to do so assign responsibilities to a new institution, or an existing one, that has access to relevant information, that has sharp analytical skills at both the financial and macroeconomic levels, and that is relatively insulated from conflicts of interest.
Its analysis should be made public and could thus influence the perception of systemic risks and market behavior, thereby increasing the capacity of the financial system to self-regulate.
